Α YOUNG friend of the poet, called Paetus, had been drowned in the course of a voyage to Egypt, whither he was bound ou some trading venture. Assumiug therefore that lust for gold was the cause of his frieud’s end, Propertius describes with much pathos the circum- stances of his death, and moralises upon the avarice of man and the rash daring which it inspires. It is one of the most beautiful of his pieces, full of an exquisite tender pathos, and showing a high imaginative capacity, such as is rarely to be found in ancient poetry, sor feeling and interpreting the wilder moods of nature. This poem would alone be enough to refute the common idea that Propertius was a mere love poet, whose oue and only inspiratiou was found in Cynthia. On the contrary, it raises the presumptiou that Cynthia did as much to degrade or divert his muse as to create it, and fills onef3with regret that he did not devote his genius to nobler themes.
